## 3. Build instructions (Makefile)

Create a directory `pcapng/` and put the two files inside it:

```
pcapng/
│─ pcapng.mli
│─ pcapng_stubs.cpp
│─ Makefile
```

```make
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Makefile – builds a tiny OCaml library "pcapng"
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
OCAMLBUILD   ?= ocamlbuild
OCAMLFLAGS   = -use-ocamlfind -pkg unix
CXX          = g++
CXXFLAGS    = -std=c++17 -Wall -O2 -fPIC
LIBNAME      = pcapng

all: $(LIBNAME).cma

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1) Compile the C++ stub as a PIC object that OCaml can link.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
$(LIBNAME).o: pcapng_stubs.cpp
	$(CXX) $(CXXFLAGS) -c $< -o $@

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2) Build the OCaml library (bytecode).  The .cma will contain the
#    compiled stub as a C object.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
$(LIBNAME).cma: $(LIBNAME).o
	$(OCAMLBUILD) $(OCAMLFLAGS) $(LIBNAME).cma \
	  -ccopt -L. -ccopt -l$(LIBNAME) -cclib -l$(LIBNAME)

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Clean
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
clean:
	$(OCAMLBUILD) -clean
	rm -f $(LIBNAME).o

.PHONY: all clean
```

Running `make` produces `pcapng.cma`, which you can link into any OCaml
program:

```sh
ocamlfind ocamlc -package pcapng -linkpkg my_program.ml -o my_program
```

